#Remove rows 74 and 76 from my data. 
Ladybird<-Ladybird[-c(74,76,17), ]

#Removal of NA results
Ladybird<-Ladybird %>%
  drop_na(Mass.per.area)

#Changing the data type
Ladybird<-Ladybird %>%
  mutate(Sex=as.factor(Sex))
Ladybird<-Ladybird %>%
  mutate(Mass.per.area=as.numeric(Mass.per.area))
Ladybird<-Ladybird %>%
  mutate(Colour.morph=as.factor(Colour.morph))

#Rounding the data up,so the data is count data
ceiling(Ladybird$Right.mean)
```

## How the relationship of vigour/condition and size varies with colour morph and sex in Adalia bipunctata. 

## Abstract: 

The condition/vigour of an individual is an important concept in ecology. Countless methods are used as markers for estimating the condition/vigour of an individual. There is no consensus on the most appropriate marker.  This report investigate the relationship of the time taken for a.bipunctata to right itself once tipped over, a measure of vigour/condition and the size(g/mm2) in different Sex and colour morphs. To investigate the relationship between right time and size(g/mm^2) a general linear mode; with the size of a.bipunctata as a continuous variable against the right time as a continuous predictor. Sex and colour morph were integrated into the general linear model as factorial predictor. All my models showed no-significant relationships with right time(p>0.05). A significant interaction effect was observed in colour morph(p>0.05).

## Introduction: 

Body size is linked to an organism’s vigour/condition. Changes in the body size have been shown to affect the survivability of individuals and population, also ecosystem function through various size dependent process. Understanding body size variation and the relationship to condition/vigour is therefore likely to shed light on lager size dependent process in organism(Honĕk, A. 1993). In this report I will be investigating the relationship of the time taken for a.bipunctata to right itself once tipped over, a measure of vigour/condition and the size(g/mm^2) in different Sex and colour morph.


## How the size (g/mm^2) of Adalia bipunctata effects the vigour/condition of long beetles. 

I hypothesised an inversely proportional relationship between size and vigour/condition of A.bipunctata. Given the test for vigour/condition is the how long it took A.bipuncata to right themselves once being tipped, I considered that larger A.bipuncata may have more difficulties in righting themselves once being tipped than smaller A. bipunctata. 
To investigate this hypothesis, I investigated the relationship between the size(g/mm^2) and the right time(s) as a count. This was fitted as a generalised linear model with a poison error distribution and a log linker. A quasi-likelihood model was fitted to account for the over-dispersion of the data. 
An type II ANOVA (F=0.7577, Df:1, P>0.05, R^2=0.01679739) of my model showed that there is no significant relationship between the size of A.bipunctata and the vigour/condition. The general linear mode show that for every 1g/mm^2 in size there is an average log increase of 1411.276 for the time needed for the A bipunctata to right itself. When the Size of A.bipunctata is zero the log intercept is 2.086. 
Despite there being no significant relationship between right time(s) and body size, there is a positive correlation between right time(s) and body size(g/mm2) in my data sets. 
In an experiment were fecundity is measured as a form of condition/vigour a significant relationship was observed between fecundity in genus Nephotettic and viviparous and body mass (Gunnarsson Bengt 1999). In a separate study when all other factors were considered for, the survivability of spiders during the winter months and the body mass of the spider was not statistically significant (H Merida 1997). These examples show that the relationship between body mass and vigour/condition is not consistent across all arthropods. Different environmental factors may affect this relationship. 
Researchers investigating the condition of Arthropods consistently use different morphological measurements of arthropods as a measure of condition/vigour. The right time is not used as a measurement of condition/vigour. If, the right time is an acceptable form of measuring the vigour and condition of A.bipuncata then the relationship observed in the model is consistent with these findings. 

```{r echo=FALSE}
#General linear Model
model_count_no_inter <- glm(Right.mean~Mass.per.area, data=Ladybird, family=quasipoisson(link="log"))
summary(model_count_no_inter) #Note that the interaction effect :sex was removed because the ANOVA results suggested that there was no interaction effect in my model. 
#Overdipressed 

rsq(model_count_no_inter) #0.01679739

model_count_no_inter <- lm(Right.mean~Mass.per.area, data=Ladybird)
summary(model_count_no_inter)


