```{r echo=FALSE, error=FALSE}

Model_count_no_inter_plot<-Ladybird %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=Mass.per.area,
             y=Right.mean))+
  geom_point(aes(x=Mass.per.area,
                 y=Right.mean))+
  theme_minimal()+
  geom_smooth(method="lm", size=1.5,se = FALSE,fullrange=TRUE)+
  scale_y_log10()+
  theme_minimal()+
  labs(x="Body wight to size ratio(g/mm^2)",
       y="Log () time take for A.bipunctata to\n right itself once tipped over(s)",
       title="The relationship between the right \n time and size in A.bipunctata ",
       caption = "Data originally supplied by Dr Jen Perry")+
  theme_classic()+
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle=39, vjust=1, hjust=1, color = "black", size= 10),
        axis.text.y =element_text(color= "black", size=10), 
        axis.title = element_text(colour="black", size=10, face="bold"), 
        plot.title = element_text(family="Helvetica", face="bold", size= (12)),  
        plot.caption = element_text(color = "Grey49",size=10, face = "italic"), 
        panel.background = element_rect(fill = 'grey98'), 
        plot.background= element_rect(fill='grey98'), 
        panel.grid.major.y = element_line("slategrey", size=0.3),
        legend.title=element_blank())+
  scale_x_continuous(expand = c(0, 0), limit=c(0, 0.0015))
Model_count_no_inter_plot
```

## How the relationship between size (g/mm2) of Adalia bipunctata and the vigour/condition of long beetles varies between sexes. 

I hypothosised that the relationship between the size of A.bipuctata and the vigour/condition of long beetles may vary with the sex of the species. Given that there is a negative relationship between size(g/mm^2) and right mean(s), differences in male and female body size may result in the relationship between size and vigour/condition varying between sex. 
To test this hypothesis, I compared body size as a continuous variable and Sex as a factorial predictor, the interaction term is the right time(s) as a count. This was fitted as a generalised linear model with a poison error distribution and a log linker. A quasi-likelihood model was fitted to account for the over-dispersion of the data. 
No significant interaction effect of size and sex (X^2 ~1,76 =4933.6, p>0.05), suggests that that relationship between increasing the size and right mean is mostly the same across males and females. 
When the body size is zero for males the log body vigour/condition is 3.0075 and when the body size is zero for female the log vigour/condition is 3.1218. The difference between the intercepts is 0.1144. The difference between male and female vigour/condition when the body size is zero is small and insignificant. The log increase in vigour/condition when the body size increases by 1 in females is 61.1049. The log increases in vigour/condition when the body size increases by 1 in males is 852.3601. The rate difference between males and female is 913.4650. There is a considerable difference of the rate of change of the two models, this account for the stepper gradient of male birds. As the body sized increases in males the right mean increases at a considerably higher rate than female birds (X2=0.18990, p>0.05, R^2F=0.005001863, R^2M= 0.094497).
In a meta-analysis investigating how the body size of male and female effects the condition/vigour of odonates female body size was significantly positively correlative with the clutch size and longevity; both are measures of vigour/condition in the odonates. Body size of males was too significantly positively correlated with the longevity and various other measures of condition/vigour. Interestingly, in non-territorial male’s body size appears to have a much more significant impact on the condition/vigour of the species. The ladybird too is non-territorial, this may account for why males body size is correlated stronger to vigour/condition than female (N.Sokolovska, 2000). 

```{r echo=FALSE, results='hide', include=FALSE, message = FALSE, warning = FALSE}
#General linear Model
#Sex
model_count <- glm(Right.mean~Mass.per.area+Sex+Mass.per.area:Sex, data=Ladybird, family=quasipoisson(link="log"))
summary(model_count) #Note that the interaction effect :sex was removed becauses the ANOVA results suggested that there was no interaction effect in my model. 
#Overdepression is ...

Ladybird$Sex <- recode_factor(Ladybird$Sex, F = "Female", M = "Male")
Ladybird$Sex <- factor(Ladybird$Sex, levels = c("Female","Male"))

main_effect_model <- glm(Right.mean~Mass.per.area+Sex, data=Ladybird, family =quasipoisson(link="log"))

anova(model_count, main_effect_model, test="Chisq")  #Keep the interactive term             
car::Anova(model_count, type="III")


