## Conclusion:

The results show that there is a non-significant positive correlation between the body size and the vigour/condition of A.bipunctata. The relationship between body size, right time varies considerably with sex. No significant interaction effect was observed for the Male and female. Despite the absence of a significant interaction effect there were considerable differences in the log right time when the body size increases by 1 in males and female. A significant interaction effect between the body size, right time of typical and melanic colour morphs was observed. However, my ability to make conclusions form the data are affected by the sample size of melanic A.bipunctata. These finding provide additional evidence for the use of measurements of body size as a measure for vigour/condition. A positive correlation is observed between body size and vigour/condition.  The body size (g/mm^2) is a poor measure of vigour/condition, as indicated by the R^2 measurements for my model. Despite this there is a positive non-significant correlation between the body size and vigour. No significant difference between Sex and measures of vigour/condition, but male A.bipunctata may have a different relationship due to non-territorial behaviour. Why non-territorial behaviour in male arthropods results in body mass having a different relationship with vigour/condition is not yet understood. Little information has been published highlighting how the colour morph in arthropods affects the vigour/condition. This report may highlight a potential area of research. The limited sample size of melanic individuals makes it difficult to draw strong conclusion form analysis of the data. But there is a strong interaction effect between typical and melanic individuals. Highlighting the need to investigate this with a greater sample size. 
Individuals with better body condition/vigour have an increased likelihood of survival in unfavourable conditions. In my model I examined how the right time, a measure of the vigour/condition varies with the size(g/mm2). Despite, the right time being a useful measures of vigour/ condition other markers for vigour/condition have frequently been used. Potential alternatives are lifespan, reproductive success, migration success, number of fit offspring are all possible alternatives (M.Knapp 2013). Several studies have opted to use the length, width and body mass in as continuous variables in a multiple linear regression model (J.Peig 2010) . This report has fails to show that body size is positively related to vigour/condition of A.bipunctata, but there were several non-significant relationships that still show a trend. Much of my modelling was a poor fit. Alterations to measurements of vigour and size of A.bipunctata may improve the strength of the statistical analysis and thus allow to for more robust analysis and conclusion. 

